{"key":"post-13555251","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13555251</id>\n<content>Oyster shells are worthless in a casing layer other than for texture, and vermiculite is better at providing that anyway.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Calcium carbonate won't raise the pH appreciably during the short life span of a casing. Egg shells are great in a garden where they have years to break down.&amp;nbsp; However, the lifespan of a casing layer is measured in weeks, not years or even months.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You want hydrated lime to raise the pH.&amp;nbsp; Get it at animal feed stores if your local plant nursery doesn't carry it.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13556779</next>\n<prev>13554687</prev>\n<first>13554574</first>\n<last>13556779</last>\n<when>1291010236</when>\n<utime>11/29/10 07:57 AM</utime>\n</post>"}